{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3153409,"name":"david","username":"howlongismyname","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/howlongismyname/{size}/134767_2.png","created_at":"2023-02-27T02:04:53.814Z","cooked":"

We need help with electrical reliability for long term use. We’re having issues with disconnects and need to do a full systems check after a full pdh replacement, and we don’t have much institutional knowledge about electrical robustness.

If anyone is near by Bellevue, Washington and is experienced with making robust electrical systems and is free this someday week, please send me a DM.

We meet Monday, Tuesday, Thursday from 3-7, and Saturday 10-6

We might have spare merch we could give you, but I’m not sure until Monday if we have any.

Thank you!

Ferrule the ends of wires, inspecting the end for stray wire hairs. Use a real ferrule crimper. Use the correct length ferrules. Pull test EVERYTHING. Use wago 221 connectors for non solder connections. Pull test everything. Zip tie your wiring so that it will NOT move. Pull test everything.

Not in town, but I’ll piggy back on the ferrule train…

We just found out that we’ve been using an incorrectly calibrated ferrule crimper! It was set to one of the lowest crimp settings. A mentor noticed, dialed it to a tighter crimp, and now everything passes the pull test.
